# Hash Tables – Notes (Slide 1–25)

## 🔹 Direct Addressing
- Idea: index = k  
- Each key has its own slot  
- No collisions  
- Time: O(1)  
- Problem: requires large array (size = key universe)

## 🔹 Hash Tables (Idea)
- Use hash function:  
  h(k) → index in table  
- Reduces large key universe to smaller array  
- Problem: collisions

## 🔹 Collisions
- Occurs when:
  h(k1) = h(k2), k1 ≠ k2  
- Unavoidable (pigeonhole principle)

## 🔹 Chaining
- Structure:
  T = array  
  T[i] = linked list  

- Multiple elements stored in same index

Example:
T[1] → [21 → 31]

## 🔹 Operations (Chaining)

### Insert:
- Compute h(k)
- Insert element in T[h(k)]
- Typically insert at head → O(1)

### Search:
- Compute h(k)
- Traverse linked list in T[h(k)]

### Delete:
- Remove element from linked list
- O(1) if doubly linked list (given pointer)

## 🔹 Load Factor
- α = n / m  
  n = number of elements  
  m = table size  

- Represents average chain length

## 🔹 Runtime (Chaining)
- Insert: O(1)
- Search: O(1 + α)
- Delete: O(1 + α)

## 🔹 Key Insight
- Good hash function → small α → fast  
- Bad hash function → large α → slow  

## 🔹 When is it O(1)?
- When α is constant (bounded)
- If α grows with n → runtime becomes O(n)

## 🔹 Intuition
- Hash table = array (fast access) + linked lists (handle collisions)
- Performance depends on distribution of keys
